{{2009<U+2013>10 Big Ten men's basketball standings}}
The '''2009<U+2013>10 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season''' marked the continuation of the annual tradition of competitive [[basketball]] among [[Big Ten Conference]] members that began in 1904. On October 16, 2009 five schools celebrated [[Midnight Madness (basketball)|Midnight Madness]] to mark the beginning of the [[2009<U+2013>10 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]].<ref name=FthMMoF>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtennetwork.com/sports/mbasketball/story.asp?list_id=47&story_id=3371914|title=Five teams host Midnight Madness on Friday|accessdate=2009-10-16|date=2009-10-14|publisher=[[Big Ten Network]]}}</ref>

[[2009<U+2013>10 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]], [[2009<U+2013>10 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]], and [[2009<U+2013>10 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|Purdue]] ended the season tied for the conference championship with 14&ndash;4 records, followed by [[2009<U+2013>10 Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team|Wisconsin]] at 13&ndash;5. In the [[2010 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]], Ohio State defeated [[2009<U+2013>10 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]] for the championship and [[Evan Turner]] was named most outstanding player.  The conference earned five bids to the [[2010 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]] by the Co-Champions, runner-up and tournament runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031410aaa.html|title=Five Big Ten Teams Selected to 2010 NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=2010-03-14|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  Big Ten teams posted a 9&ndash;5 overall record including three sweet sixteen appearances and one final four appearance. Two members of the conference received invitations to play in the [[2010 National Invitation Tournament]].  The Big Ten posted a 2&ndash;2 record in the tournament.

2010 [[Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year]] Evan Turner received multiple first team [[2010 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans]] and National Player of the Year recognitions.  [[Tr<U+00E9>von Hughes]], [[E'Twaun Moore]], [[Kalin Lucas]] and [[Robbie Hummel]] also received various All-American recognitions.  Moore was also recognized as an [[Academic All-American]].

==Preseason==
On October 16, 2009 [[2009<U+2013>10 Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball team|Illinois]], [[Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball|Indiana]], [[2009<U+2013>10 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]], [[2009<U+2013>10 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]], and [[2009<U+2013>10 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]] celebrated [[Midnight Madness (basketball)|Midnight Madness]].<ref name=FthMMoF/>  Michigan State, [[2009-10 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|Purdue]] and Michigan were ranked in the top 25 by all preseason polls.  The entire 2008<U+2013>09 All-Big Ten Conference first-team returned: [[Manny Harris]] <small>[[2008-09 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|MICH]]</small>; [[Kalin Lucas]] <small>[[2008-09 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|MSU]]</small>; [[Evan Turner]] <small>[[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|OSU]]</small>; [[Talor Battle]] <small>[[2008<U+2013>09 Penn State Nittany Lions men's basketball team|PSU]]</small>; and [[JaJuan Johnson]] <small>[[2008<U+2013>09 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|PUR]]</small>.<ref name=BTCA2MBTS/> The 24-member Big Ten media panel selected Lucas as the preseason conference player of the year and he was joined on the first team preseason All-Big Ten team by Harris, Turner, Battle and [[Robbie Hummel]] of [[2008<U+2013>09 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team|PUR]].<ref name=DBTCMSNMBPFBM>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/102909aaa.html|title=Defending Big Ten Champion Michigan State Named Men's Basketball Preseason Favorite By Media: Reigning Big Ten Player of Year Kalin Lucas Tabbed Preseason Player of Year|accessdate=2009-10-30|date=2009-10-29|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  The same media panel selected Michigan State as the preseason conference favorite followed by Purdue and Ohio State.<ref name=DBTCMSNMBPFBM/>

Various publications released their preseason predictions for conference standings and All-Big Ten teams. 

