==Regular season==
[[File:20091112 Evan Turner cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Evan Turner]] of [[2009<U+2013>10 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]] set new [[Big Ten]] records for number of career and single season Player of the Week awards during the 2009<U+2013>10 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season.]]
;November
The season opened with the Big Ten Conference holding the leadership with six team ranked among the [[2009<U+2013>10 NCAA Division I men's basketball season#Pre-season_polls|preseason top 25]] in both the [[AP Poll]] and the [[Coaches' Poll]], setting a new conference record for most teams ranked to open a season.  The season also opened with the entire 2008&ndash;09 first team All-Big Ten players returning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/110909aab.html|title=Big Ten Weekly Men's Basketball Release - Week 1: Ohio State tips off 2009-10 campaign Monday night in Columbus|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-11-09|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Both [[Manny Harris]] (November 14) and [[Evan Turner]] (November 9) recorded [[triple double]]s in the opening week of the season marking the first times a Big Ten player has accomplished the feat since January 13, 2001.<ref name=MaOSGFWHo2S/>  Six of the eleven conference teams started at least one freshman.<ref name=Week2>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/111609aab.html|title=Big Ten Weekly Men's Basketball Release-Week 2: Six teams ranked in both the AP and ESPN/USA Today polls|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-11-16|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  The following week, three schools (Michigan State, Illinois and Iowa) participated in [[ESPN]]'s Tuesday, November 17 24-hour hoops marathon across its family of networks (ESPN, [[ESPN2]], [[ESPNU]] & [[ESPN360.com]]).<ref name=Week2/>  Michigan State's [[Magic Johnson]] and [[Jud Heathcote]] were inducted into the [[National Collegiate Basketball Hall of Fame]] on November 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/112309aab.html|title=Big Ten Men's Basketball Weekly Release: Week 3: Six teams remain among the nation's top 25|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-11-23|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> With his 341st victory, [[Tom Izzo]] became Michigan State's all-time leader in basketball coaching victories.<ref name=Week4>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/113009aaf.html|title=Big Ten Men's Basketball Weekly Release: Week 4: 11th Annual Big Ten/ACC Challenge highlights week|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-11-30|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  Turner became the second player in conference history to be named conference player of the week three weeks in a row.<ref name=Week4/> On November 28, both Ohio State and Michigan State scored 100 points,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=293320113|title=(2) Michigan St  106 (5-1, 0-0 away); Massachusetts 68 (2-4, 2-1 home)|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-11-28|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=293330194|title=St. Francis (PA) 47 (1-5, 0-3 away); (18) Ohio St 110 (5-1, 4-0 home)|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-11-28|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> marking the first time two conference teams have done so since December 22, 1997.<ref name=Week5/>

;December
For the second time this season, two teams scored 100 points on the same night on December 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=293400194|title=E Michigan  60 (5-3, 2-2 away); (15) Ohio St 111 (7-1, 6-0 home)|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-12-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=293392509|title=Buffalo 65 (3-3, 2-1 away); (6) Purdue 101 (7-0, 4-0 home)|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-12-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  For the first time in eleven attempts, the Big Ten won the [[ACC <U+2013> Big Ten Challenge]].<ref name=Week5>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/120709aac.html|title=Big Ten Men's Basketball Weekly Release: Week 5: Purdue remains undefeated at 7-0; Seven teams ranked or receiving votes in latest polls.|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-12-07|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  In his 275th game, [[Bo Ryan]] reached the 200-win milestone with [[Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball]]. In the same week, [[Tom Crean]] raised his record to 200-&ndash;125.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/121409aab.html|title=Men's Basketball Weekly Release: Week 6: Purdue remains undefeated in non-conference play, joining 10 other teams in the nation.|accessdate=2009-12-30|date=2009-12-14|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>   The Big Ten entered intraconference play tied with the [[2009<U+2013>10 Big East Conference men's basketball season|Big East Conference]] by having five ranked teams. Northwestern entered conference play on its longest winning streak in 16 years (9) and Purdue reached the 11&ndash;0 mark for the second time and had a perfect record at the end of December for the first time since the 1936&ndash;37 team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/122809aad.html|title=Men's Basketball Release: Week 8: The 105th season of Big Ten Basketball Tips off this Week; Purdue remains undefeated and Northwestern is on a nine-game win streak.|accessdate=2010-08-15|date=2009-12-28|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>

;January
Purdue ran its record to 14&ndash;0 to start the season, which tied the [[Glenn Robinson]]-led [[1993<U+2013>94 Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball team]] for the best start in school history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=300052509|title=Hummel, Moore lead No. 4 Boilermakers to 14-0 start, tying program mark|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2010-01-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Four Big Ten athletes ([[Talor Battle]], Harris, [[Trevon Hughes]] and Lucas) were named as finalists for the 2010 [[Bob Cousy Award]] to lead all conferences. Harris, Lucas, Robbie Hummel and Turner were also selected Midseason Top-30 finalists for the 2010 [[John Wooden Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/011110aac.html|title=Men's Basketball Release: Week 10: The Big Ten has featured eight teams in the AP Top 25 this season; Boilers set a new school record for 35 consecutive weeks ranked in the AP Poll.|accessdate=2010-02-08|date=2010-01-11|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> On January 12, Hummel and Turner became only the third opposing Big Ten players to post 30 points against each other in one night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/011810aac.html|title=Men's Basketball Release: Week 11: The Big Ten is tied for the national lead for most wins over AP Top 25 non-conference opponents with 10|accessdate=2010-02-08|date=2010-01-18|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=300122509|title=Turner scores 23 of 32 in second half after Hummel's first-half heroics|accessdate=2010-02-12|date=2010-01-12|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref> Michigan State established a new school record by winning its first eight conference games and extended the streak to nine by the end of the month.<ref>{{vcite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=300260130|title=No. 5 Michigan State reaches 8-0 in Big Ten after tough test from Michigan|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2010-01-26|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{vcite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=300300127|title=Summers shines as Michigan State improves to 9-0 in Big Ten play|accessdate=2010-04-18|date=2010-01-30|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref>

;February
On February 8 Turner recorded his fifth Conference Player of the Week award and eighth of his career surpassing the former conference record held by [[Glenn Robinson]] and [[Jim Jackson (basketball)|Jim Jackson]], who each had seven career and tied Robinson's single-season record with five.<ref name="IMaOSTSWL"/>  Two weeks later he set the single-season record with his sixth recognition when he averaged 24.5 points, 8.5 rebounds and 5.5 assists against two ranked opponents (No. 4 Purdue and at No. 11 Michigan State).<ref name=OSETNBTPotW/> Three Big Ten players made the February Top 30 midseason [[Naismith College Player of the Year]] watchlist: Hummel, Lucas and Turner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naismithawards.com/PressBox/PressReleases/02242010NaismithTrophyMidseasonCandidates/tabid/168/Default.aspx|title=Naismith Trophy Midseason Candidates Announced: Winner to be Revealed at the Final Four in Indianapolis|accessdate=2010-03-07|date=2010-02-24|publisher=AT&T Intellectual Property}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030210aab.html|title=Men's Basketball Release: Week 17: Michigan State, Ohio State, Purdue and Wisconsin have all secured first-round tournament byes|accessdate=2010-03-07|date=2010-03-02|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  Hummel and Turner were selected among the 16 finalists for the 2010 [[Oscar Robertson Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportswriters.net/usbwa/news/2010/oscar100217.html|title=USBWA Names Finalist For 2010 Oscar Robertson Trophy|accessdate=2010-03-10|date=2010-02-17|publisher=[[United States Basketball Writers Association]]}}</ref>

;March
Turner was selected as one of six finalists for the [[Bob Cousy Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030910aab.html|title=Men's Basketball Release: Week 18: 13th Annual Big Ten Tournament Tips Off Thursday|accessdate=2010-03-16|date=2010-03-09|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  Lucas, Hummel and Turner were included on the final 26-man ballot for the Wooden Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woodenaward.com/?p=494|title=2010 Wooden Award Ballot Sent to Voters|accessdate=2010-03-17|date=2010-03-15|publisher=John R. Wooden Award}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.byucougars.com/Filing.jsp?ID=13699|title=Fredette Named to Wooden Award Ballot|accessdate=2010-03-17|date=2010-03-15|publisher=BYU Athletics|author=Chilton, Kyle}}</ref>

==Rankings==

{{See also|2009<U+2013>10 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings}}

During the season, seven of the Big Ten teams received enough votes to be ranked and an eight team received voted during several weekly polls.  Michigan State and Purdue were ranked during every weekly poll during the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/rankings/_/year/2010/week/3/seasontype/3|title=2010 NCAA Men's Basketball Rankings - Postseason (Mar. 29)|accessdate=2010-08-11|date=2010-03-29|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

